stylometry: Some of the things that the output tells you are; The maximum possible profit, the minimum possible profit, the standard deviation, and the average profit you will get. You want to look at all these things but some are more important than others. Probably the most important one is STD-DEV becasue it shows you how relaible the data to the quantity you are testing is. If you have great max. profit numbers but a huge STD-DEV that means the data isn't very relaible and that it is a huge risk. You want a choice with a relativly low STD-DEV. The next one I look at is the average profit becuase it is a good solid number to fall back on and you can pretty much rely on the fact that your profit will be in that ball park. So when I make a desicion I want a higher-end average profit with a low STD-DEV.
